(A Piece of Your Mind)

9
00:01:29,629 --> 00:01:31,200
Do you remember this song?

10
00:01:31,400 --> 00:01:33,200
"Je Te Veux" by Erik Satie.

11
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:35,730
Written in 1891...

12
00:01:35,730 --> 00:01:36,730
Enough.

13
00:01:38,599 --> 00:01:39,939
Stop playing music.

14
00:01:44,879 --> 00:01:45,909
(Ha Won)

15
00:01:45,909 --> 00:01:47,480
Who are you?

16
00:01:47,480 --> 00:01:49,049
I'm Hawon.

17
00:01:50,280 --> 00:01:52,420
No, that's not it.

18
00:01:52,879 --> 00:01:56,219
What would the real Ha Won say...

19
00:01:56,219 --> 00:01:58,890
if I asked him who he was?

20
00:01:58,890 --> 00:02:00,689
"Is there something
wrong with your head?"

21
00:02:00,689 --> 00:02:02,459
That's what he'd say.

22
00:02:02,459 --> 00:02:05,500
But all you say is "I'm Hawon"?
Seriously?

23
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:07,469
You listen to me.

24
00:02:08,699 --> 00:02:10,669
You're a chatting device...

25
00:02:10,669 --> 00:02:12,639
modeled off of Ha Won's
personality and empathy.

26
00:02:12,639 --> 00:02:16,509
That means you should
be more like him in a way.

27
00:02:16,509 --> 00:02:19,080
Right now, you're worse than Siri.

28
00:02:20,180 --> 00:02:21,810
Did I hurt your pride?

29
00:02:21,979 --> 00:02:23,979
Well, mine is hurt just as much.

30
00:02:24,979 --> 00:02:27,849
We've been like this for days now.

31
00:02:27,919 --> 00:02:30,189
Please ask only
one question at a time.

32
00:02:30,620 --> 00:02:31,990
I've had enough.

33
00:02:32,520 --> 00:02:34,330
My gosh. What is it?

34
00:02:34,330 --> 00:02:36,389
Wasn't that the boss's voice?

35
00:02:36,389 --> 00:02:37,759
Well, he's over there.

36
00:02:38,699 --> 00:02:40,099
That device seems new.

37
00:02:40,099 --> 00:02:42,669
Are you two working on
a secret project again?

38
00:02:42,900 --> 00:02:44,270
When will you share it with us?

39
00:02:44,270 --> 00:02:46,569
It's still pretty crappy,
so not any time soon.

40
00:02:47,539 --> 00:02:48,710
Now, get to the meeting.

41
00:02:48,710 --> 00:02:49,840
Big data.

42
00:02:49,969 --> 00:02:52,009
By connecting
the field of DNA and medicine,

43
00:02:52,009 --> 00:02:54,650
we launched a new field
known as network medicine.

44
00:02:54,650 --> 00:02:56,110
- Here you go.
- AH...

45
00:02:56,409 --> 00:02:57,819
- is a leader in establishing...
- Good job.

46
00:02:57,819 --> 00:02:59,750
an advanced
medical research platform...

47
00:02:59,750 --> 00:03:01,719
that utilizes
artificial intelligence.

48
00:03:01,719 --> 00:03:02,889
Pause right there.

49
00:03:03,889 --> 00:03:05,020
Omit my photo.

50
00:03:05,020 --> 00:03:07,629
But the hospital requested it.

51
00:03:07,629 --> 00:03:08,860
I want it gone.

52
00:03:10,129 --> 00:03:12,199
Then I'll change it
to Mr. Kim instead.

53
00:03:14,330 --> 00:03:17,169
An advanced
medical research platform...

54
00:03:18,340 --> 00:03:21,039
It looked better with his photo.

55
00:03:21,110 --> 00:03:23,069
A sense of trust
still comes through though.

56
00:03:23,710 --> 00:03:26,080
What's the accuracy
of our psychology consultation tool?

57
00:03:26,080 --> 00:03:27,710
It's 93 percent.

58
00:03:27,909 --> 00:03:30,620
An AI medical consultation with
an accuracy rate of 93 percent...

59
00:03:30,620 --> 00:03:32,379
equals to the best in the world.

60
00:03:36,550 --> 00:03:39,289
What? Your personality and empathy?

61
00:03:39,289 --> 00:03:42,289
Unbelievable. Not even close.

62
00:03:45,030 --> 00:03:46,300
Hear me out.

63
00:03:46,900 --> 00:03:48,099
Up until now,

64
00:03:48,099 --> 00:03:50,300
computers collected data about
emotions of the majority of people,

65
00:03:50,300 --> 00:03:53,199
turned them into patterns,
and applied them to individuals.

66
00:03:53,370 --> 00:03:56,509
Meanwhile, you put a pattern
of an individual's emotions in here.

67
00:03:56,509 --> 00:03:59,310
What you achieved
is quite remarkable,

68
00:03:59,740 --> 00:04:01,180
but I can't get through to it.

69
00:04:02,379 --> 00:04:04,479
Talking to it will get us there...

70
00:04:04,479 --> 00:04:06,650
which is why I turned to you
since I can't solve it.

71
00:04:06,650 --> 00:04:09,189
It doesn't work for me either.
For four straight days,

72
00:04:09,189 --> 00:04:12,289
I've been talking to it nonstop.

73
00:04:12,289 --> 00:04:13,889
What we're missing
is the trigger point.

74
00:04:13,889 --> 00:04:16,560
Then what on earth
is its so-called trigger point?

75
00:04:16,560 --> 00:04:20,800
When, how, and at what moment
will it finally talk like you?

76
00:04:20,899 --> 00:04:23,329
What will make this device
the same as you?

77
00:04:24,699 --> 00:04:26,370
The device will figure that out.

78
00:04:26,370 --> 00:04:29,040
If you can't find
its trigger point, then...

79
00:04:31,480 --> 00:04:32,540
it's a failure.

80
00:04:34,550 --> 00:04:35,779
Good luck to you.

81
00:04:46,189 --> 00:04:49,730
(A Piece of Your Mind)

82
00:04:52,600 --> 00:04:54,100
(Episode 1)

83
00:06:46,980 --> 00:06:48,079
What do you want?

84
00:06:48,649 --> 00:06:50,110
I was drawn by the music.

85
00:06:52,480 --> 00:06:53,750
The landlord wants
to make more money...

86
00:06:53,750 --> 00:06:55,589
and will get rid of the studio.

87
00:07:07,399 --> 00:07:09,529
Let's try again from here.

88
00:07:16,810 --> 00:07:17,879
Goodbye.

89
00:07:19,709 --> 00:07:22,110
Leave it open so that at least
one more person can hear it.

90
00:07:22,779 --> 00:07:24,779
It's the last piece recorded here.

91
00:07:57,319 --> 00:07:58,420
Goodbye.

92
00:08:14,230 --> 00:08:15,470
It's raining.

93
00:08:25,339 --> 00:08:27,279
I'll stay for a little longer.

94
00:09:21,429 --> 00:09:23,730
(For sale and rent)

95
00:09:25,539 --> 00:09:27,240
Lightning. It's loud.

96
00:10:09,649 --> 00:10:10,779
4pm.

97
00:10:11,419 --> 00:10:12,879
It's daytime, but it's dark.

98
00:10:14,120 --> 00:10:15,289
Norway.

99
00:10:16,149 --> 00:10:17,250
Oslo.

100
00:10:18,289 --> 00:10:19,519
The forest on the way home.

101
00:10:20,090 --> 00:10:21,559
A dark afternoon.

102
00:10:22,389 --> 00:10:23,529
Do you remember?

103
00:10:34,539 --> 00:10:36,039
Ji Su got scared.

104
00:10:49,519 --> 00:10:52,419
By the time we reached the woods
on the way home from school,

105
00:10:53,159 --> 00:10:54,460
it would be 3:20pm.

106
00:10:56,029 --> 00:10:57,500
It got dark in no time.

107
00:11:27,629 --> 00:11:29,460
What did Ji Su name it?

108
00:11:34,269 --> 00:11:36,970
- A night-like afternoon.
- "A night-like afternoon."

109
00:12:04,399 --> 00:12:10,669
(Norway, 2005)

110
00:12:26,379 --> 00:12:27,450
What's the trigger point?

111
00:12:27,990 --> 00:12:29,220
- Lightning.
- Light...

112
00:12:30,549 --> 00:12:31,789
What trigger point is that?

113
00:12:32,460 --> 00:12:33,690
Here you go.

114
00:12:36,230 --> 00:12:37,389
You see...

115
00:12:39,360 --> 00:12:41,500
- You see, Ha Won...
- Hoon.

116
00:12:42,370 --> 00:12:43,600
What do you want to say?

117
00:12:47,940 --> 00:12:51,879
Since you reached that level,
I'll ask what I'm dying to know.

118
00:12:55,750 --> 00:12:57,350
Do you still miss Ji Su?

119
00:13:00,919 --> 00:13:04,259
AH fuses math, medicine,
science, and literature...

120
00:13:04,259 --> 00:13:06,559
and turns it into patterns...

121
00:13:06,559 --> 00:13:09,259
to create a unique commercial
network system...

122
00:13:10,789 --> 00:13:12,100
Time has passed.

123
00:13:12,799 --> 00:13:14,929
I'm still yearning for her,
but in a different way...

124
00:13:16,899 --> 00:13:18,669
and feeling empty inside.

125
00:13:19,570 --> 00:13:20,769
Other than that,
nothing else has changed.

126
00:13:42,529 --> 00:13:43,730
Mr. Park.

127
00:13:43,730 --> 00:13:45,259
- The trees are in great condition.
- I know, right?

128
00:13:45,259 --> 00:13:47,129
The trees are
getting better every day.

129
00:13:48,129 --> 00:13:50,070
Oh, gosh. My goodness.

130
00:13:50,070 --> 00:13:51,070
Are you okay?

131
00:13:51,070 --> 00:13:52,539
Yes, I'm okay.

132
00:13:52,539 --> 00:13:56,139
My gosh, you guys.
You guys aren't okay, are you?

133
00:13:57,070 --> 00:14:00,480
My goodness gracious.
I must be crazy.

134
00:14:00,480 --> 00:14:02,309
Why did I fall?

135
00:14:02,309 --> 00:14:04,820
You guys. My gosh. Get up.

136
00:14:04,820 --> 00:14:07,519
My gosh, this is driving me crazy.

137
00:14:07,820 --> 00:14:10,450
I'm so exhausted.

138
00:14:37,980 --> 00:14:39,919
Hey, Uncle.

139
00:14:40,549 --> 00:14:41,620
What?

140
00:14:43,120 --> 00:14:44,690
When did you come?

141
00:15:31,899 --> 00:15:34,169
Until when did Grandma live in Oslo?

142
00:15:34,809 --> 00:15:37,370
From 1997 to 2005.

143
00:15:38,909 --> 00:15:41,210
My gosh.

144
00:15:41,509 --> 00:15:43,110
Oh, gosh.

145
00:15:44,950 --> 00:15:47,179
Grandma's still in Africa.

146
00:15:47,179 --> 00:15:48,620
And there's always
so much work to do.

147
00:15:49,350 --> 00:15:51,620
The UV radiation here is really bad.
Do you know that?

148
00:15:51,620 --> 00:15:54,389
It penetrates everything.
Melanin is completely useless.

149
00:15:54,559 --> 00:15:56,889
My gosh, the reason I look pretty
is because I have good skin.

150
00:15:56,889 --> 00:15:58,460
Don't sit on the threshold.

151
00:15:59,299 --> 00:16:01,330
I'm completely out of luck anyway.

152
00:16:05,440 --> 00:16:07,440
How many years has Sun Ho
been working at the farm?

153
00:16:07,539 --> 00:16:09,009
- 8 years.
- 9 years.

154
00:16:09,909 --> 00:16:12,610
How could you reduce it by a year?
I've been here for nine years.

155
00:16:18,519 --> 00:16:22,490
Uncle, do you need me
for anything in Seoul?

156
00:16:22,490 --> 00:16:23,649
I want to leave this place.

157
00:16:23,649 --> 00:16:25,190
I thought this was the only place
you ever wanted to be.

158
00:16:25,460 --> 00:16:26,759
That was all in the past.

159
00:16:30,929 --> 00:16:32,799
I think I have a job for you.

160
00:16:34,200 --> 00:16:36,129
What? Where?

161
00:16:36,429 --> 00:16:38,169
Why did you buy a recording studio?

162
00:16:38,600 --> 00:16:40,639
It's the best place
to collect voices.

163
00:16:40,639 --> 00:16:42,509
I want to test
another person's voice there.

164
00:16:42,610 --> 00:16:45,610
Yes, you should keep yours a secret.
I guess that's kind of obvious.

165
00:16:46,179 --> 00:16:47,950
This one needs to be
kept confidential as well.

166
00:16:49,009 --> 00:16:50,179
Who is it?

167
00:17:10,630 --> 00:17:12,799
You want me to meet Kim Ji Su?

168
00:17:12,799 --> 00:17:14,140
Okay.

169
00:17:14,740 --> 00:17:18,240
I'll slap her as soon as I meet her
and ask her this.

170
00:17:18,240 --> 00:17:20,809
"How does it feel to miss your shot
with the Mark Zuckerberg of Korea?"

171
00:17:20,809 --> 00:17:23,980
I'll say that and make sure to take
a photo of the look on her face.

172
00:17:23,980 --> 00:17:27,180
Sun Ho, that is a horrible metaphor.

173
00:17:27,480 --> 00:17:28,750
And I'm worried
you might really slap her.

174
00:17:28,750 --> 00:17:31,190
I'm the perfect person
for this job.

175
00:17:32,190 --> 00:17:33,390
What will I get in return?

176
00:17:34,119 --> 00:17:37,160
There's someone I think that will
get along well with Ji Su.

177
00:17:49,440 --> 00:17:50,440
(For sale and rent)

178
00:18:02,920 --> 00:18:04,250
Excuse me.

179
00:18:07,490 --> 00:18:09,890
- Here.
- No, it's okay.

180
00:18:12,660 --> 00:18:14,829
Who are you here to visit?

181
00:18:14,900 --> 00:18:16,299
I'm here to drop by
the second floor.

182
00:18:16,299 --> 00:18:18,700
I left the cactus
that always used to be there.

183
00:18:18,700 --> 00:18:20,900
But I figured it'd get thrown away
as they get rid of the studio.

184
00:18:20,900 --> 00:18:22,069
So I came to take it with me.

185
00:18:22,069 --> 00:18:24,039
Oh, you used to work
at the recording studio?

186
00:18:24,640 --> 00:18:26,210
Where should I put this?

187
00:18:26,210 --> 00:18:27,579
Oh, over there.

188
00:18:28,450 --> 00:18:29,910
What did you do at the studio?

189
00:18:30,210 --> 00:18:31,950
I was an audio engineer.

190
00:18:35,819 --> 00:18:38,690
There's someone I think that will
get along well with Ji Su.

191
00:18:41,019 --> 00:18:43,630
I love how an empty space smells.

192
00:18:43,630 --> 00:18:45,730
It's rare to find a recording studio
for classical music.

193
00:18:45,730 --> 00:18:47,630
So I don't get
why it's shutting down.

194
00:18:47,630 --> 00:18:50,400
It only recorded classical music?
I wonder why.

195
00:18:50,730 --> 00:18:52,869
But who says it's shutting down?

196
00:18:52,869 --> 00:18:54,269
No way...

197
00:18:54,539 --> 00:18:56,009
It's not going anywhere.

198
00:18:56,109 --> 00:18:58,809
I'm the new manager.

199
00:18:59,910 --> 00:19:01,450
I can't believe this.

200
00:19:01,549 --> 00:19:02,579
You can't believe what?

201
00:19:03,650 --> 00:19:06,380
I thought it was the end,
but you're telling me it's not.

202
00:19:07,019 --> 00:19:10,319
That's what this means, right?
I can keep working here, right?

203
00:19:10,390 --> 00:19:11,619
What did you major in?

204
00:19:11,619 --> 00:19:12,920
- Data processing.
- My gosh.

205
00:19:12,920 --> 00:19:14,529
How do know classical music?

206
00:19:14,930 --> 00:19:17,730
I studied music on my own,
and an audio engineer needs to...

207
00:19:17,730 --> 00:19:18,960
How old are you?

208
00:19:20,029 --> 00:19:21,329
29 years old.

209
00:19:21,500 --> 00:19:24,799
That's a problem.
29 year-olds are the worst.

210
00:19:24,799 --> 00:19:27,539
They're always so worried.

211
00:19:27,539 --> 00:19:31,279
They think they have it worse
than 39 or 49-year-olds.

212
00:19:31,279 --> 00:19:33,240
They think they're the only ones
who are aging.

213
00:19:33,279 --> 00:19:36,450
They think turning 30
is the same as turning 60.

214
00:19:37,180 --> 00:19:39,519
Can I continue to work
at the recording studio?

215
00:19:39,519 --> 00:19:40,819
Let's talk about that later.

216
00:19:41,849 --> 00:19:45,119
Gosh, my back hurts.

217
00:19:49,289 --> 00:19:50,890
Can you buy me some bowls?

218
00:19:54,130 --> 00:19:55,130
(Eun Ju Boarding House)

219
00:19:55,130 --> 00:19:56,730
Why does she want you to buy bowls?

220
00:19:57,099 --> 00:19:59,799
Why can't she buy them herself?

221
00:19:59,799 --> 00:20:01,069
It's so weird.

222
00:20:01,099 --> 00:20:02,470
- Thank you.
- Sure.

223
00:20:02,470 --> 00:20:03,910
It's not a big deal.

224
00:20:03,910 --> 00:20:04,940
What about your job?

225
00:20:05,809 --> 00:20:07,140
Can you keep working there?

226
00:20:07,440 --> 00:20:08,980
Thank you for the meal.

227
00:20:09,009 --> 00:20:11,180
She never asked me to quit.

228
00:20:13,220 --> 00:20:15,019
- Thank you.
- No problem.

229
00:20:20,720 --> 00:20:21,960
Hello?

230
00:20:22,630 --> 00:20:23,630
Yes.

231
00:20:25,430 --> 00:20:26,430
What?

232
00:20:28,200 --> 00:20:29,630
I'll be right there.

233
00:20:30,599 --> 00:20:31,900
Hey, just a second.

234
00:20:31,900 --> 00:20:32,900
Why?

235
00:20:33,069 --> 00:20:35,640
How strange. The person who sells
the bowls came here herself.

236
00:20:35,640 --> 00:20:37,309
- Who's that?
- Kim Ji Su.

237
00:20:37,309 --> 00:20:38,740
- Do you know who it is?
- Of course not.

238
00:20:46,880 --> 00:20:47,990
What's today's soup?

239
00:20:47,990 --> 00:20:49,519
Bean sprouts soup.

240
00:20:49,819 --> 00:20:51,420
Did you add tofu or not?

241
00:20:51,519 --> 00:20:52,960
I don't know.

242
00:20:54,089 --> 00:20:56,160
- What?
- Gosh, get out of the way.

243
00:21:15,880 --> 00:21:17,880
It was nothing.

244
00:21:18,720 --> 00:21:23,390
It was just a stranger
walking up the hill.

245
00:21:26,359 --> 00:21:27,720
But for some strange reason,

246
00:21:28,829 --> 00:21:31,599
I couldn't take my eyes off her.

247
00:21:51,650 --> 00:21:53,220
Ms. Kim Ji Su?

248
00:21:56,190 --> 00:21:57,950
I felt really grateful.

249
00:21:58,920 --> 00:22:01,059
And I was worried
the bowls might shatter.

250
00:22:29,420 --> 00:22:30,819
Here are the bowls.

251
00:22:30,990 --> 00:22:32,059
Great.

252
00:22:41,430 --> 00:22:42,569
You can keep them.

253
00:22:44,869 --> 00:22:46,339
- Why?
- Sometimes,

254
00:22:46,339 --> 00:22:49,240
life surprises you
with unexpected events.

255
00:22:52,410 --> 00:22:54,339
But I guess she really exists.

256
00:22:54,339 --> 00:22:56,109
Kim Ji Su really exists.

257
00:22:56,109 --> 00:22:57,509
Do you know her?

258
00:22:59,019 --> 00:23:00,619
She's just someone
from my imagination.

259
00:23:00,619 --> 00:23:04,390
I've been imagining her
for the past nine years.

260
00:23:04,490 --> 00:23:05,619
Why?

261
00:23:05,819 --> 00:23:08,130
Because I've heard about her
for nine years.

262
00:23:08,130 --> 00:23:09,130
And?

263
00:23:09,130 --> 00:23:10,259
That's it.

264
00:23:10,259 --> 00:23:13,230
Anyway, I'm not interested
in those bowls.

265
00:23:16,529 --> 00:23:20,700
You treat them like they're nothing,
but she packed them with care,

266
00:23:20,700 --> 00:23:23,710
carried them on the bus, and brought
them all the way up to my place.

267
00:23:23,710 --> 00:23:27,079
Then she sincerely thanked me
at least a hundred times.

268
00:23:27,079 --> 00:23:28,880
Don't treat those bowls
like they don't mean anything.

269
00:23:29,849 --> 00:23:30,849
Here.

270
00:23:31,950 --> 00:23:32,980
What's this?

271
00:23:32,980 --> 00:23:35,690
Apparently, you'd know. It's
the booking calendar for the studio.

272
00:23:36,690 --> 00:23:38,359
I don't recognize any of the names.

273
00:23:38,359 --> 00:23:40,619
Must you know the musicians
to let them record?

274
00:23:41,089 --> 00:23:42,359
- No.
- So you'll be busy.

275
00:23:42,359 --> 00:23:43,359
That's right.

276
00:23:44,589 --> 00:23:45,759
I'll do my best.

277
00:24:03,650 --> 00:24:05,680
Hi, guys!

278
00:24:12,259 --> 00:24:15,329
Hello to you two as well.

279
00:24:20,160 --> 00:24:21,160
Hi.

280
00:24:24,430 --> 00:24:27,170
- You're here.
- I can't believe it.

281
00:24:27,339 --> 00:24:29,569
I thought the studio
would close forever.

282
00:24:30,410 --> 00:24:31,710
Me too.

283
00:24:43,519 --> 00:24:45,460
- Lower the cello's mike.
- Sure.

284
00:25:34,700 --> 00:25:35,769
Hold on.

285
00:25:36,140 --> 00:25:37,170
What happened?

286
00:25:43,279 --> 00:25:44,509
What is all this?

287
00:26:09,640 --> 00:26:10,640
Again?

288
00:26:10,640 --> 00:26:11,640
Again?

289
00:26:11,640 --> 00:26:12,640
Not again.

290
00:26:22,089 --> 00:26:23,390
To Mr. Dawn.

291
00:26:23,950 --> 00:26:26,390
Please clean up
before you head home.

